{{Infobox dot-com company |name = The Hawaii Project |logo = |logo size = <!-- width in pixels, with "px" suffix --> |logo alt = |collapsible = <!-- "yes" or "no" --> |screenshot = |screenshot size = <!-- width in pixels, with "px" suffix --> |screenshot alt = |caption = |company_type = Private |location = [[Sudbury, Massachusetts]], [[Kailua, Honolulu County, Hawaii]] |country = [[United States]] |locations = |area served = International |key people = {{unbulleted list|Mark Watkins, founder}} |industry = Books |services = Book Recommendations |employees = |url = {{url|http://www.thehawaiiproject.com/}} |website type = Book Recommendations |registration = Not required |users = |launched = {{start date and age|2015|Jun|09}} }}
'''The Hawaii Project''' is a personalized book discovery engine.<ref name=xconomy>{{cite web| url=http://www.xconomy.com/boston/2015/04/02/hawaii-project-taps-search-to-suggest-right-books-for-the-beach/| title=Hawaii Project Taps Search to Suggest Right Books for the Beach| author=Michael Davidson| date=2 April 2015| publisher=Xconomy}}</ref> The Hawaii Project provides personalized book recommendations and access to current book news. It tracks curated sources of interesting books and articles, uncovering new texts that align with a user's interests, their favorite authors and current events.<ref name="betaboston">{{cite web| url=http://www.betaboston.com/news/2015/04/23/this-kickstarter-project-wants-to-find-you-the-perfect-beach-book/| title=Hawaii Project Wants to Find You The Perfect Beach Book| author=Vijee Venkatraman| date=23 April 2015| publisher=Beta Boston}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/columnist/2016/02/24/these-gadgets-help-you-keep-your-new-years-resoultions/80805008/|title=Best tech to keep your workouts on track|access-date=2016-06-30}}</ref> Users of The Hawaii Project can follow authors and particular sources of writing about books to get alerts about relevant information. It is privately funded.
==Company history== The Hawaii Project was founded in 2014 by Mark Watkins. Prior to The Hawaii Project, he was CEO and co-founder of [[Goby (search engine)]], a mobile recommendation engine for finding things to do, since acquired by Telenav. Prior to that, he was VP of Engineering for Endeca, a search company acquired by [[Oracle Corporation]] for $1.075B.<ref name="oracle-acquisition">{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/Boston/businessupdates/2011/10/oracle-buys-endeca/tHRB2UzIBhbhkB5V5RhrFN/index.html |title=Oracle buys Endeca |work=Boston.com |date=2011-10-18 |accessdate=2011-10-18 |last=Farrell |first=Michael B.}}</ref>
The origin of the company was rooted in the founder's frustration at not finding out about new books from his favorite authors.<ref name=bostinno>{{cite web| url=http://bostinno.streetwise.co/2015/04/14/best-new-books-the-hawaii-project-tells-you-what-to-read/| title=This New Startup Hunts Down the Books You're Bound to Love| author=Rebecca Strong| date=14 April 2015| publisher=Bost Inno| accessdate=11 October 2014}}</ref>
